## Finding: Phase 2 Has Only 4 Skills For A Domain That Requires 15-20

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence:
First-principles decomposition of what a "Design Phase" must own in a world-class software development framework reveals roughly 15-20 distinct atomic responsibilities. Phase 2 currently covers only 4: ARA (architecture synthesis methodology), deployment modes (multi-environment compliance), feature architecture (documentation), and schema standards (data model documentation). The following atomic responsibilities have zero coverage:

1. Architecture Decision Records (ADRs) — no skill for capturing WHY architectural choices were made
2. Technology selection / tech stack evaluation — no structured process for choosing database, frameworks, languages, cloud providers with documented tradeoffs
3. System integration design — how services/systems communicate (REST vs GraphQL vs gRPC vs messaging, event contracts, integration topologies)
4. Security architecture design — threat modeling (STRIDE, PASTA), trust boundaries, security zones, attack surface mapping BEFORE build begins
5. Performance / scalability modeling — capacity planning, SLOs, load modeling, bottleneck identification during design
6. Cost architecture / FinOps design — cloud cost modeling, resource sizing, budget projections during design
7. API contract design (separate from api_design in Phase 3) — designing the API contract as a design artifact, consumer-first / contract-first
8. Data flow and privacy design — PII classification, data residency decisions, GDPR/HIPAA data flow mapping
9. Dependency mapping and risk assessment — external dependencies, vendor lock-in analysis, supply chain risk
10. Design review process — structured peer review / design critique workflow before build begins
11. Non-functional requirements (NFRs) specification — latency, availability, durability, consistency, observability requirements
12. Error budget and reliability design — SLI/SLO/SLA definitions, error budget policy
13. Component interface design — defining contracts between internal components before they are built
14. Testing strategy design — deciding the testing pyramid shape, coverage targets, testing infrastructure requirements at design time

### Proposed Resolution:
Create 10+ new skills for Phase 2 covering ADRs, tech-stack-selection, security-threat-modeling, performance-modeling, cost-architecture, api-contract-design, data-privacy-design, dependency-risk-assessment, design-review-process, and nfr-specification.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Every downstream phase (3-7) is affected. Build (Phase 3) begins implementation without architectural constraints documented. Secure (Phase 4) has no threat model to audit against. Ship (Phase 5) has no SLO targets to validate. Maintenance (Phase 7) has no ADR trail to understand why decisions were made.
================================================================

## Finding: No Architecture Decision Record (ADR) Skill

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence:
ADRs are the canonical mechanism for recording architectural decisions — context, decision, consequences, and status (proposed/accepted/superseded/deprecated). Without ADRs, every future team member, AI agent, and contributor must reverse-engineer WHY the architecture is the way it is. ARA produces a vision, decomposition, and dependency graph but explicitly produces NO "decision record" artifact that tracks alternatives considered and rationale. The feature_architecture skill produces documentation of what exists but does not capture why choices were made over alternatives. No Phase 2 skill currently triggers creation of an ADR document.
### Proposed Resolution:
New skill: `architecture_decision_records` in Phase 2. Trigger: "Record architectural decision for [choice]" / "Create ADR for [decision]". Scope: Provides MADR (Markdown Architectural Decision Records) format, decision log template, status lifecycle (Proposed → Accepted → Deprecated → Superseded), and a searchable ADR index. Integrates with SSoT in Phase 12.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Without ADRs, Phase 3 (Build) implements against unexplained constraints. Phase 6 (Handoff) cannot explain system design to new teams. Phase 7 (Maintenance) makes decisions that contradict earlier reasoning, causing architectural drift.
================================================================

## Finding: No Technology Selection / Stack Evaluation Skill

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence:
A design phase must include a structured process for selecting technologies — choosing between PostgreSQL vs MongoDB, REST vs GraphQL, monolith vs microservices, React vs Vue, etc. The current Phase 2 assumes technology choices are already made (ARA is technology-agnostic at decomposition but produces no selection artifact; deployment_modes assumes NestJS + React + specific providers). There is no skill that guides the user through a weighted decision matrix, tradeoff analysis, or tech radar consultation. The framework implicitly locks every project into NestJS + React + PostgreSQL without documenting why.
### Proposed Resolution:
New skill: `technology_selection` in Phase 2. Trigger: "Evaluate technology choices for [project]" / "Tech stack decision for [decision]". Scope: Provides a weighted evaluation matrix template, defines evaluation criteria (team familiarity, community support, performance, licensing, cost, security track record), produces a Technology Selection Record (TSR), and flags high-risk or novel technology choices for escalation.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 3 (Build) has 59+ skills that are almost entirely NestJS/React-specific. If a project uses Django, Go, or Spring Boot, there are Phase 3 skills for those stacks but no Phase 2 design skill that would route to the correct Phase 3 skills or document why that stack was chosen.
================================================================

## Finding: No Security Threat Modeling Skill At Design Time

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence:
Security architecture must begin at the design phase, not at Phase 4 (Secure). The OWASP threat modeling process (STRIDE: Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, Elevation of Privilege) should produce a threat model during design. The current Phase 2 has no such skill. The `deployment_modes` skill touches on security only in that it flags Sovereign mode data privacy. The `feature_architecture` skill has a "Security Considerations" section but it is template-level and not a threat modeling exercise. Phase 4 has a `security_audit` skill (referenced in spec_build Phase 5) but this is a post-hoc audit, not design-time threat modeling. "Security by design" requires the threat model BEFORE API and schema are defined.
### Proposed Resolution:
New skill: `security_threat_modeling` in Phase 2. Trigger: "Threat model for [feature/system]" / "Run STRIDE analysis on [design]". Scope: Guides a STRIDE threat identification session against the ARA output, produces a threat register with risk ratings (likelihood × impact), defines security controls to address each threat, and creates trust boundary diagrams. Output becomes a security requirements document that feeds Phase 5 (security_audit checks against this register).
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 3 (Build) implements without security constraints defined. Phase 4 (Secure) audits against no baseline. Phase 5 (Ship) may ship features with unaddressed threats because the security review was never design-grounded.
================================================================

## Finding: No Non-Functional Requirements (NFR) Specification Skill

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence:
NFRs (latency targets, throughput, availability %, consistency model, data durability, regulatory compliance tiers) must be specified at design time because they constrain every implementation choice. ARA's Phase 2 (Atomic Decomposition) asks "what is the minimum this needs to function?" but does not systematically capture NFRs. The quality checklist checks that success metrics are defined at vision level, but does not require SLO-level precision. No Phase 2 skill produces an NFR specification document. The schema_standards skill documents data structure but not data access latency requirements or volume expectations that would influence index design.
### Proposed Resolution:
New skill: `nfr_specification` in Phase 2. Trigger: "Define NFRs for [system]" / "Specify performance and reliability requirements for [feature]". Scope: Captures latency (p50, p95, p99), throughput (requests/second), availability (99.9% vs 99.99%), data durability, consistency model (eventual vs strong), compliance tiers (SOC2, HIPAA, GDPR), and scale targets. Produces an NFR contract that feeds both Phase 3 (implementation constraints) and Phase 5 (acceptance criteria for shipping).
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 3 (Build) implements without knowing if the feature needs to handle 10 or 10,000 concurrent users. Phase 5 (Ship) has no performance acceptance criteria. Phase 7 (Maintenance) has no SLO baseline to detect regressions.
================================================================

## Finding: ARA Skill Is Methodology-Heavy But Produces No Standardized Artifact Schema

### Gap Type: SHALLOW_COVERAGE
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence:
The ARA skill is well-designed as a methodology document but it has a critical gap: its five output documents (Vision Document, Architecture Document, Implementation Plan, Gap Checklist) have no standardized schema or template that downstream skills can reliably parse. The quality checklist validates process completeness but does not define the machine-readable or agent-readable format of outputs. The `spec_build` skill invokes ARA at Phase 2 and expects "dependency map, component breakdown, integration points" but ARA's Dependency Ordering output (Phase 5) is described as a visual representation in text form with no consistent structure.
### Proposed Resolution:
Extend ARA SKILL.md to include mandatory artifact schemas: JSON schema for the Dependency Map, table format for the Component Breakdown, and a standardized Integration Points document template. These outputs should be parseable by downstream Phase 3 skills.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 3 spec_build Phase 2 gate condition ("All dependencies identified and mapped") cannot be automatically verified without a structured artifact format.
