## Finding: Reverse Test — "Perfectly Completed Design" Would Have Explicit Data Privacy Design; Framework Has None

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence:
Working backward from a GDPR/HIPAA-compliant product: the design phase MUST produce a data privacy design document covering: PII field classification (which schema fields contain personal data), data residency requirements (must EU user data stay in EU?), data retention policies (auto-delete after N days), right-to-erasure implementation strategy (how to delete a user's PII from all tables/backups), consent management architecture (where is consent recorded, how is it propagated), and third-party data sharing agreements (what data goes to OpenAI, Supabase, etc.).

The `schema_standards` skill has a status/owner governance section but zero privacy classification. The `deployment_modes` skill notes "Data stored in cloud. May be used to train third-party AI unless opted out" as a privacy note but provides no design guidance. There is no Phase 2 skill that produces a data privacy design artifact.

Delta: A GDPR-regulated project cannot complete Phase 2 with current skills because no skill produces the data flow mapping required for a GDPR Article 30 Record of Processing Activities (RoPA).
### Proposed Resolution:
New skill: `data_privacy_design` in Phase 2. Trigger: "Design data privacy for [system]" / "GDPR/HIPAA design for [feature]". Scope: PII field classification matrix, data residency decisions, retention policy specification, erasure strategy (technical implementation design for right-to-erasure), consent record architecture, third-party data processor inventory, and GDPR Article 30 RoPA template.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 4 (Secure) cannot audit GDPR compliance without a data privacy design. Phase 5 (Ship) may ship features that are immediately non-compliant. Phase 7 (Maintenance) inherits privacy debt that is expensive to remediate.
