## Finding: Reverse Test — "Perfectly Completed Design" Would Have Explicitly Ruled On Consistency Model; Framework Is Silent

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence:
Working backward: a system design that handles concurrent users MUST have explicitly decided its consistency model: strong consistency (all reads see the latest write) vs eventual consistency (reads may see stale data) vs causal consistency. This decision affects: cache invalidation strategy, whether optimistic or pessimistic locking is used, WebSocket event ordering guarantees, and how conflicts are resolved in Hybrid deployment mode where local and cloud data diverge.

The `feature_architecture` skill mentions "Concurrency & Race Conditions" under the University Heist Analysis but this is a documentation section for existing code, not a design-time decision framework. The ARA skill Phase 3 asks about race conditions as part of reverse condition mapping but provides no framework for selecting the appropriate consistency model.

Delta: No Phase 2 skill produces a consistency model decision artifact. Developers make ad-hoc consistency choices during Phase 3 implementation.
### Proposed Resolution:
This finding should be folded into the NFR specification skill (proposed in Loop 1) which must include consistency model as a required NFR decision point.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 3 (Build) may mix strong-consistency patterns (database transactions) with eventual consistency patterns (caching) without conscious design, creating subtle correctness bugs.
