## Finding: Framework Ignores ISO/IEC 25010 Quality Model (Industry Standard For Software Quality)

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence:
ISO/IEC 25010 defines the Software Quality Model with 8 quality characteristics: Functional Suitability, Performance Efficiency, Compatibility, Usability, Reliability, Security, Maintainability, and Portability. A world-class design phase explicitly addresses all 8 characteristics. Phase 2 currently covers:
- Security: partially (deployment_modes mentions AI data privacy, but no threat modeling)
- Portability: partially (deployment_modes covers multi-mode deployment)
- Functional Suitability: partially (ARA Phase 1 Vision State)

Zero coverage for:
- Performance Efficiency: no performance requirements, no capacity model
- Compatibility: no interoperability requirements, no data exchange format standards
- Usability: no accessibility requirements, no UX design constraints
- Reliability: no fault tolerance design, no recovery time objectives (RTO/RPO)
- Maintainability: no modularity requirements, no changeability analysis, no testability requirements at design time

This is not a minor gap — ISO 25010 is the foundational standard for software quality specification. A design phase that ignores 6 of 8 quality characteristics will systematically produce systems that fail on those dimensions.
### Proposed Resolution:
Add an ISO 25010 Quality Characteristics section to the ARA quality checklist as a mandatory Phase 4 (Gap Synthesis) output. Each characteristic must be explicitly addressed or documented as "Not Applicable" with justification. This does not require new skills but requires updating ARA's cross-cutting concerns inventory.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 3 (Build) implements features without quality constraints on Reliability, Performance Efficiency, Usability, or Maintainability. Phase 5 (Ship) ships to users without knowing if reliability or performance targets are met.
================================================================

## Finding: Framework Has No C4 Model Architecture Diagrams (Industry Standard For Architecture Communication)

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence:
The C4 Model (Simon Brown, widely adopted since 2018) defines four levels of architecture diagrams: Context (system in its environment), Container (runtime boundaries: apps, databases, queues), Component (modules within a container), and Code (classes/functions). This is the industry standard for communicating software architecture to different audiences (executives → Context, architects → Container, developers → Component, code reviewers → Code). The framework's Phase 2 has no C4 model skill. The `feature_architecture` skill uses mermaid sequenceDiagram and graph TD but these are ad-hoc, not C4-structured. ARA's Dependency Ordering (Phase 5) produces a dependency graph but this is not a C4 diagram.

Without C4 diagrams, the framework lacks a structured, audience-appropriate way to communicate architecture. Industry teams (from startups to enterprises) routinely use C4 for onboarding and design review.
### Proposed Resolution:
New skill: `c4_architecture_diagrams` in Phase 2. Trigger: "Create C4 diagrams for [system]" / "Generate architecture diagrams for [project]". Scope: Produces all 4 C4 diagram levels using mermaid syntax, defines which level is appropriate for which audience (stakeholders, developers, reviewers), and integrates with the `feature_architecture` and ARA outputs. Provides mermaid templates for each C4 level.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 6 (Handoff) has no standardized architecture diagrams to give to clients or incoming teams. Phase 3 developers must read ARA's text-based dependency descriptions instead of visual Container diagrams.
================================================================

## Finding: Framework Ignores DORA Metrics At Design Time (Industry Standard For Delivery Performance)

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence:
DORA (DevOps Research & Assessment) defines 4 key metrics for software delivery performance: Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Change Failure Rate, and Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR). Elite performers target: deployment multiple times per day, lead time under 1 hour, change failure rate under 5%, MTTR under 1 hour. These must be designed for at the architecture level — they cannot be retrofitted. Designing for DORA elite performance requires: feature flags (for deployment frequency without user impact), automated rollback mechanisms (for MTTR), progressive delivery patterns (for change failure rate), and CI/CD pipeline architecture (for lead time). No Phase 2 skill addresses DORA metrics or designs for delivery performance targets. The framework goes from design directly to build without specifying delivery performance targets.
### Proposed Resolution:
Add a "Delivery Architecture" section to ARA Phase 4 (Gap Synthesis): required DORA targets must be specified and the architectural implications of each target must be documented. For example, "Deployment frequency: multiple per day → requires feature flags, database migration strategy for zero-downtime deploys, and automated smoke tests."
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 5 (Ship) and Phase 3 (git_workflow, docker_development) implement CI/CD without delivery performance targets. The framework may produce systems that are architecturally incapable of elite DORA performance.
================================================================

## Finding: Framework Ignores OpenAPI/AsyncAPI First Design (Industry Mandate For API Governance)

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence:
The industry standard for API development is "API-first" or "contract-first" design: write the OpenAPI 3.0 or AsyncAPI 2.x specification BEFORE writing implementation code. This enables: parallel frontend/backend development against the contract mock, contract testing (Pact, Dredd), automatic SDK generation for consumers, API governance linting (Spectral), and breaking change detection. Phase 3's `api_design` skill shows NestJS implementation code with Swagger decorators (`@ApiProperty`, `@ApiOperation`) but this is a code-first approach where the OpenAPI spec is generated FROM the code. The industry API governance approach (API-first) generates the spec first and validates code against it. No Phase 2 skill produces a standalone OpenAPI specification before any code is written.

This finding directly relates to the `api_contract_design` gap identified in Loop 2 but approaches it from the industry standards angle: the industry mandate is contract-first, the framework practices code-first.
### Proposed Resolution:
Confirmed from industry standards perspective. The `api_contract_design` skill (proposed in Loop 2) is the correct resolution. Additional requirement: the skill must explicitly specify that the OpenAPI spec is the SOURCE OF TRUTH, not a generated artifact. Phase 3 `api_design` should reference the Phase 2 OpenAPI spec and validate implementation against it.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Without an API-first Phase 2 artifact, frontend (Phase 3 `frontend_patterns`) cannot develop in parallel against a stable contract. Third-party integrators have no spec to build against before the backend is complete.
================================================================

## Finding: Framework Ignores Accessibility (WCAG 2.1) At Design Time (Legal Mandate In Many Jurisdictions)

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence:
WCAG 2.1 (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines) is a legal requirement in the EU (EN 301 549), UK (Equality Act 2010), USA (ADA/Section 508), and Australia (ATAG). Accessibility must be designed from the beginning — retrofitting is 30x more expensive than designing for accessibility from the start. Phase 2 has no skill for accessibility design: no WCAG 2.1 conformance level target (A, AA, AAA), no accessible color palette specification, no keyboard navigation design, no screen reader interaction design, no ARIA role/landmark design for complex components. Phase 3 has a `ui_polish` skill and a `liquid_glass_design` skill but neither is an accessibility design skill. The `ui_polish` skill in Phase 3's spec_build (Phase 10) references tooltip/help text but not accessibility conformance.

For any product shipping to EU, UK, or USA markets, skipping accessibility design is a legal risk.
### Proposed Resolution:
New skill: `accessibility_design` in Phase 2. Trigger: "Design accessibility for [product/feature]" / "Define WCAG requirements for [project]". Scope: Sets WCAG 2.1 conformance target, defines keyboard navigation patterns for complex UI components, specifies ARIA roles and landmarks, defines color contrast requirements, establishes accessible form validation pattern, and produces an accessibility requirements checklist that Phase 3 frontend implementation must satisfy.
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 3 `frontend_patterns` and `ui_polish` implement UI without accessibility requirements. Phase 5 (Ship) may ship legally non-compliant products. Phase 7 (Maintenance) inherits accessibility debt.
================================================================

## Finding: Framework Has No Design-Level Performance Budget (Core Web Vitals Industry Standard)

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence:
Google's Core Web Vitals (LCP, INP, CLS) are now ranking factors for SEO and de facto industry standards for web performance. Setting a performance budget (max LCP: 2.5 seconds, max CLS: 0.1, max INP: 200ms) at design time constrains architectural choices: whether to use SSR vs CSR, whether to use a CDN, how to design lazy loading, what image optimization strategy to use. No Phase 2 skill sets a performance budget. Phase 3 `frontend_patterns` implements UI without performance constraints. This connects to the NFR gap (Loop 1) but specifically references the industry-standard Core Web Vitals metric set.
### Proposed Resolution:
Add Core Web Vitals targets to the NFR specification skill (proposed in Loop 1) as required performance budget items for any web-facing product. Additionally, add to the ARA quality checklist: "Performance budget defined for frontend (LCP, INP, CLS targets)."
### Cross-Phase Impact:
Phase 3 frontend implementation choices (bundle size, hydration strategy, image handling) are made without performance budget constraints. Phase 5 (Ship) may ship with poor Core Web Vitals scores that harm SEO.
================================================================

